# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: biostatistics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] Biostatistical modeling forms an important part of numerous modern biological theories.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] Genetics studies, since its beginning, used statistical concepts to understand observed experimental results.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] Some genetics scientists even contributed with statistical advances with the development of methods and tools.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] Gregor Mendel started the genetics studies investigating genetics segregation patterns in families of peas and used statistics to explain the collected data.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] In the early 1900s, after the rediscovery of Mendel's Mendelian inheritance work, there were gaps in understanding between genetics and evolutionary Darwinism.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] Francis Galton tried to expand Mendel's discoveries with human data and proposed a different model with fractions of the heredity coming from each ancestral composing an infinite series.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] He called this the theory of "Law of Ancestral Heredity".
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] His ideas were strongly disagreed by William Bateson, who followed Mendel's conclusions, that genetic inheritance were exclusively from the parents, half from each of them.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] This led to a vigorous debate between the biometricians, who supported Galton's ideas, as Raphael Weldon, Arthur Dukinfield Darbishire and Karl Pearson, and Mendelians, who supported Bateson's (and Mendel's) ideas, such as Charles Davenport and Wilhelm Johannsen.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] Later, biometricians could not reproduce Galton conclusions in different experiments, and Mendel's ideas prevailed.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] By the 1930s, models built on statistical reasoning had helped to resolve these differences and to produce the neo-Darwinian modern evolutionary synthesis.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] Solving these differences also allowed to define the concept of population genetics and brought together genetics and evolution.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] The three leading figures in the establishment of population genetics and this synthesis all relied on statistics and developed its use in biology.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] These and other biostatisticians, mathematical biologists, and statistically inclined geneticists helped bring together evolutionary biology and genetics into a consistent, coherent whole that could begin to be quantitatively modeled.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] In parallel to this overall development, the pioneering work of D'Arcy Thompson in *On Growth and Form* also helped to add quantitative discipline to biological study.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] Despite the fundamental importance and frequent necessity of statistical reasoning, there may nonetheless have been a tendency among biologists to distrust or deprecate results which are not qualitatively apparent.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] One anecdote describes Thomas Hunt Morgan banning the Friden calculator from his department at Caltech, saying "Well, I am like a guy who is prospecting for gold along the banks of the Sacramento River in 1849.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] With a little intelligence, I can reach down and pick up big nuggets of gold.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] Any research in life sciences is proposed to answer a scientific question we might have.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] To answer this question with a high certainty, we need accurate results.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] The correct definition of the main hypothesis and the research plan will reduce errors while taking a decision in understanding a phenomenon.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] The research plan might include the research question, the hypothesis to be tested, the experimental design, data collection methods, data analysis perspectives and costs involved.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] It is essential to carry the study based on the three basic principles of experimental statistics: randomization, replication, and local control.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] The research question will define the objective of a study.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] The research will be headed by the question, so it needs to be concise, at the same time it is focused on interesting and novel topics that may improve science and knowledge and that field.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] To define the way to ask the scientific question, an exhaustive literature review might be necessary.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] So the research can be useful to add value to the scientific community.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] Once the aim of the study is defined, the possible answers to the research question can be proposed, transforming this question into a hypothesis.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] The main propose is called null hypothesis (H0) and is usually based on a permanent knowledge about the topic or an obvious occurrence of the phenomena, sustained by a deep literature review.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] We can say it is the standard expected answer for the data under the situation in test.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] In general, HO assumes no association between treatments.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] On the other hand, the alternative hypothesis is the denial of HO.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] It assumes some degree of association between the treatment and the outcome.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] Although, the hypothesis is sustained by question research and its expected and unexpected answers.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] As an example, consider groups of similar animals (mice, for example) under two different diet systems.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] The research question would be: what is the best diet?
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] In this case, H0 would be that there is no difference between the two diets in mice metabolism (H0: μ1 = μ2) and the alternative hypothesis would be that the diets have different effects over animals metabolism (H1: μ1 ≠ μ2).
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] The hypothesis is defined by the researcher, according to his/her interests in answering the main question.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] Besides that, the alternative hypothesis can be more than one hypothesis.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] It can assume not only differences across observed parameters, but their degree of differences (*i.e.* higher or shorter).
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] Usually, a study aims to understand an effect of a phenomenon over a population.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] In biology, a population is defined as all the individuals of a given species, in a specific area at a given time.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] In biostatistics, this concept is extended to a variety of collections possible of study.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] Although, in biostatistics, a population is not only the individuals, but the total of one specific component of their organisms, as the whole genome, or all the sperm cells, for animals, or the total leaf area, for a plant, for example.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] It is not possible to take the measures from all the elements of a population.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] Because of that, the sampling process is very important for statistical inference.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] Sampling is defined as to randomly get a representative part of the entire population, to make posterior inferences about the population.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] So, the sample might catch the most variability across a population.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] The sample size is determined by several things, since the scope of the research to the resources available.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] In clinical research, the trial type, as inferiority, equivalence, and superiority is a key in determining sample size.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] Experimental designs sustain those basic principles of experimental statistics.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] There are three basic experimental designs to randomly allocate treatments in all plots of the experiment.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] They are completely randomized design, randomized block design, and factorial designs.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] Treatments can be arranged in many ways inside the experiment.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] In agriculture, the correct experimental design is the root of a good study and the arrangement of treatments within the study is essential because environment largely affects the plots (plants, livestock, microorganisms).
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] These main arrangements can be found in the literature under the names of "lattices", "incomplete blocks", "split plot", "augmented blocks", and many others.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] All of the designs might include control plots, determined by the researcher, to provide an error estimation during inference.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] In clinical studies, the samples are usually smaller than in other biological studies, and in most cases, the environment effect can be controlled or measured.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] It is common to use randomized controlled clinical trials, where results are usually compared with observational study designs such as case–control or cohort.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] Data collection methods must be considered in research planning, because it highly influences the sample size and experimental design.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] Data collection varies according to the type of data.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] For qualitative data, collection can be done with structured questionnaires or by observation, considering presence or intensity of disease, using score criterion to categorize levels of occurrence.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] For quantitative data, collection is done by measuring numerical information using instruments.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] In agriculture and biology studies, yield data and its components can be obtained by metric measures.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] However, pest and disease injuries in plants are obtained by observation, considering score scales for levels of damage.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] Especially, in genetic studies, modern methods for data collection in field and laboratory should be considered, as high-throughput platforms for phenotyping and genotyping.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] These tools allow bigger experiments, while turn possible evaluate many plots in lower time than a human-based only method for data collection.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] Finally, all data collected of interest must be stored in an organized data frame for further analysis.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] Data can be represented through tables or graphical representation, such as line charts, bar charts, histograms, scatter plot.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] Also, measures of central tendency and variability can be very useful to describe an overview of the data.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] One type of table is the frequency table, which consists of data arranged in rows and columns, where the frequency is the number of occurrences or repetitions of data.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] In the next example, we have the number of genes in ten operons of the same organism.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] Line graphs represent the variation of a value over another metric, such as time.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] In general, values are represented in the vertical axis, while the time variation is represented in the horizontal axis.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] A bar chart is a graph that shows categorical data as bars presenting heights (vertical bar) or widths (horizontal bar) proportional to represent values.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] Bar charts provide an image that could also be represented in a tabular format.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] In the bar chart example, we have the birth rate in Brazil for the December months from 2010 to 2016.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] The sharp fall in December 2016 reflects the outbreak of Zika virus in the birth rate in Brazil.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] The histogram (or frequency distribution) is a graphical representation of a dataset tabulated and divided into uniform or non-uniform classes.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] It was first introduced by Karl Pearson.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] A scatter plot is a mathematical diagram that uses Cartesian coordinates to display values of a dataset.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] A scatter plot shows the data as a set of points, each one presenting the value of one variable determining the position on the horizontal axis and another variable on the vertical axis.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] They are also called **scatter graph**, **scatter chart**, **scattergram**, or **scatter diagram**.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] The arithmetic mean is the sum of a collection of values ( ${x_{1}+x_{2}+x_{3}+\cdots +x_{n}}$ ) divided by the number of items of this collection ( ${n}$ ).
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] The median is the value in the middle of a dataset.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] The mode is the value of a set of data that appears most often.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] Box plot is a method for graphically depicting groups of numerical data.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] The maximum and minimum values are represented by the lines, and the interquartile range (IQR) represent 25–75% of the data.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] Although correlations between two different kinds of data could be inferred by graphs, such as scatter plot, it is necessary validate this though numerical information.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] For this reason, correlation coefficients are required.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] They provide a numerical value that reflects the strength of an association.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] Pearson correlation coefficient is a measure of association between two variables, X and Y.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] This coefficient, usually represented by *ρ* (rho) for the population and *r* for the sample, assumes values between −1 and 1, where *ρ* = 1 represents a perfect positive correlation, *ρ* = −1 represents a perfect negative correlation, and *ρ* = 0 is no linear correlation.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] It is used to make inferences about an unknown population, by estimation and/or hypothesis testing.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] In other words, it is desirable to obtain parameters to describe the population of interest, but since the data is limited, it is necessary to make use of a representative sample in order to estimate them.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] With that, it is possible to test previously defined hypotheses and apply the conclusions to the entire population.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] The standard error of the mean is a measure of variability that is crucial to do inferences.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] Hypothesis testing is essential to make inferences about populations aiming to answer research questions, as settled in "Research planning" section.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] *Significance level and decision rule*: A decision rule depends on the level of significance, or in other words, the acceptable error rate (α).
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] It is easier to think that we define a *critical value* that determines the statistical significance when a test statistic is compared with it.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] So, α also has to be predefined before the experiment.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] *Experiment and statistical analysis*: This is when the experiment is really implemented following the appropriate experimental design, data is collected and the more suitable statistical tests are evaluated.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] *Inference*: Is made when the null hypothesis is rejected or not rejected, based on the evidence that the comparison of p-values and α brings.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] It is pointed that the failure to reject H0 just means that there is not enough evidence to support its rejection, but not that this hypothesis is true.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] A confidence interval is a range of values that can contain the true real parameter value in given a certain level of confidence.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] The first step is to estimate the best-unbiased estimate of the population parameter.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] The upper value of the interval is obtained by the sum of this estimate with the multiplication between the standard error of the mean and the confidence level.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] The calculation of lower value is similar, but instead of a sum, a subtraction must be applied.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] When testing a hypothesis, there are two types of statistic errors possible: Type I error and Type II error.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] The significance level denoted by α is the type I error rate and should be chosen before performing the test.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] The type II error rate is denoted by β and statistical power of the test is 1 − β.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] The p-value is the probability of obtaining results as extreme as or more extreme than those observed, assuming the null hypothesis (H0) is true.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] It is also called the calculated probability.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] It is common to confuse the p-value with the significance level (α), but, the α is a predefined threshold for calling significant results.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] If p is less than α, the null hypothesis (H0) is rejected.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] In multiple tests of the same hypothesis, the probability of the occurrence of false positives (familywise error rate) increase and a strategy is needed to account for this occurrence.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] This is commonly achieved by using a more stringent threshold to reject null hypotheses.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] The Bonferroni correction defines an acceptable global significance level, denoted by α* and each test is individually compared with a value of α = α*/m.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] This ensures that the familywise error rate in all m tests, is less than or equal to α*.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] When m is large, the Bonferroni correction may be overly conservative.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] An alternative to the Bonferroni correction is to control the false discovery rate (FDR).
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] The FDR controls the expected proportion of the rejected null hypotheses (the so-called discoveries) that are false (incorrect rejections).
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] This procedure ensures that, for independent tests, the false discovery rate is at most q*.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] Thus, the FDR is less conservative than the Bonferroni correction and have more power, at the cost of more false positives.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] The main hypothesis being tested (e.g., no association between treatments and outcomes) is often accompanied by other technical assumptions (e.g., about the form of the probability distribution of the outcomes) that are also part of the null hypothesis.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] When the technical assumptions are violated in practice, then the null may be frequently rejected even if the main hypothesis is true.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] Such rejections are said to be due to model mis-specification.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] Verifying whether the outcome of a statistical test does not change when the technical assumptions are slightly altered (so-called robustness checks) is the main way of combating mis-specification.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] Model criteria selection will select or model that more approximate true model.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] The Akaike's Information Criterion (AIC) and The Bayesian Information Criterion (BIC) are examples of asymptotically efficient criteria.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] Recent developments have made a large impact on biostatistics.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] Two important changes have been the ability to collect data on a high-throughput scale, and the ability to perform much more complex analysis using computational techniques.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] This comes from the development in areas such as sequencing technologies, Bioinformatics and Machine learning (Machine learning in bioinformatics).
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] New biomedical technologies like microarrays, next-generation sequencers (for genomics) and mass spectrometry (for proteomics) generate enormous amounts of data, allowing many tests to be performed simultaneously.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] Careful analysis with biostatistical methods is required to separate the signal from the noise.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] For example, a microarray could be used to measure many thousands of genes simultaneously, determining which of them have different expression in diseased cells compared to normal cells.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] However, only a fraction of genes will be differentially expressed.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] Multicollinearity often occurs in high-throughput biostatistical settings.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] Due to high intercorrelation between the predictors (such as gene expression levels), the information of one predictor might be contained in another one.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] It could be that only 5% of the predictors are responsible for 90% of the variability of the response.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] In such a case, one could apply the biostatistical technique of dimension reduction (for example via principal component analysis).
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] Classical statistical techniques like linear or logistic regression and linear discriminant analysis do not work well for high dimensional data (i.e. when the number of observations n is smaller than the number of features or predictors p: n < p).
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] As a matter of fact, one can get quite high R2-values despite very low predictive power of the statistical model.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] These classical statistical techniques (esp. least squares linear regression) were developed for low dimensional data (i.e. where the number of observations n is much larger than the number of predictors p: n >> p).
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] In cases of high dimensionality, one should always consider an independent validation test set and the corresponding residual sum of squares (RSS) and R2 of the validation test set, not those of the training set.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] Often, it is useful to pool information from multiple predictors together.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] For example, Gene Set Enrichment Analysis (GSEA) considers the perturbation of whole (functionally related) gene sets rather than of single genes.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] These gene sets might be known biochemical pathways or otherwise functionally related genes.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] The advantage of this approach is that it is more robust: It is more likely that a single gene is found to be falsely perturbed than it is that a whole pathway is falsely perturbed.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] Furthermore, one can integrate the accumulated knowledge about biochemical pathways (like the JAK-STAT signaling pathway) using this approach.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] The development of biological databases enables storage and management of biological data with the possibility of ensuring access for users around the world.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] They are useful for researchers depositing data, retrieve information and files (raw or processed) originated from other experiments or indexing scientific articles, as PubMed.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] Another possibility is search for the desired term (a gene, a protein, a disease, an organism, and so on) and check all results related to this search.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] There are databases dedicated to SNPs (dbSNP), the knowledge on genes characterization and their pathways (KEGG) and the description of gene function classifying it by cellular component, molecular function and biological process (Gene Ontology).
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] In addition to databases that contain specific molecular information, there are others that are ample in the sense that they store information about an organism or group of organisms.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] As an example of a database directed towards just one organism, but that contains much data about it, is the *Arabidopsis thaliana* genetic and molecular database – TAIR.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] Phytozome, in turn, stores the assemblies and annotation files of dozen of plant genomes, also containing visualization and analysis tools.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] Moreover, there is an interconnection between some databases in the information exchange/sharing and a major initiative was the International Nucleotide Sequence Database Collaboration (INSDC) which relates data from DDBJ, EMBL-EBI, and NCBI.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] Nowadays, increase in size and complexity of molecular datasets leads to use of powerful statistical methods provided by computer science algorithms which are developed by machine learning area.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] Therefore, data mining and machine learning allow detection of patterns in data with a complex structure, as biological ones, by using methods of supervised and unsupervised learning, regression, detection of clusters and association rule mining, among others.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] To indicate some of them, self-organizing maps and *k*-means are examples of cluster algorithms; neural networks implementation and support vector machines models are examples of common machine learning algorithms.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] Collaborative work among molecular biologists, bioinformaticians, statisticians and computer scientists is important to perform an experiment correctly, going from planning, passing through data generation and analysis, and ending with biological interpretation of the results.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] On the other hand, the advent of modern computer technology and relatively cheap computing resources have enabled computer-intensive biostatistical methods like bootstrapping and re-sampling methods.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] In recent times, random forests have gained popularity as a method for performing statistical classification.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] Random forest techniques generate a panel of decision trees.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] Decision trees have the advantage that you can draw them and interpret them (even with a basic understanding of mathematics and statistics).
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] Random Forests have thus been used for clinical decision support systems.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] Public health, including epidemiology, health services research, nutrition, environmental health and health care policy & management.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] In these medicine contents, it's important to consider the design and analysis of the clinical trials.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] As one example, there is the assessment of severity state of a patient with a prognosis of an outcome of a disease.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] With new technologies and genetics knowledge, biostatistics are now also used for Systems medicine, which consists in a more personalized medicine.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] For this, is made an integration of data from different sources, including conventional patient data, clinico-pathological parameters, molecular and genetic data as well as data generated by additional new-omics technologies.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] The study of population genetics and statistical genetics in order to link variation in genotype with a variation in phenotype.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] In other words, it is desirable to discover the genetic basis of a measurable trait, a quantitative trait, that is under polygenic control.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] A genome region that is responsible for a continuous trait is called a quantitative trait locus (QTL).
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] The study of QTLs become feasible by using molecular markers and measuring traits in populations, but their mapping needs the obtaining of a population from an experimental crossing, like an F2 or recombinant inbred strains/lines (RILs).
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] To scan for QTLs regions in a genome, a gene map based on linkage have to be built.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] Some of the best-known QTL mapping algorithms are Interval Mapping, Composite Interval Mapping, and Multiple Interval Mapping.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] However, QTL mapping resolution is impaired by the amount of recombination assayed, a problem for species in which it is difficult to obtain large offspring.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] Furthermore, allele diversity is restricted to individuals originated from contrasting parents, which limit studies of allele diversity when we have a panel of individuals representing a natural population.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] For this reason, the genome-wide association study was proposed in order to identify QTLs based on linkage disequilibrium, that is the non-random association between traits and molecular markers.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] It was leveraged by the development of high-throughput SNP genotyping.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] In animal and plant breeding, the use of markers in selection aiming for breeding, mainly the molecular ones, collaborated to the development of marker-assisted selection.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] While QTL mapping is limited due resolution, GWAS does not have enough power when rare variants of small effect that are also influenced by environment.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] So, the concept of Genomic Selection (GS) arises in order to use all molecular markers in the selection and allow the prediction of the performance of candidates in this selection.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] The proposal is to genotype and phenotype a training population, develop a model that can obtain the genomic estimated breeding values (GEBVs) of individuals belonging to a genotype and but not phenotype population, called testing population.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] This kind of study could also include a validation population, thinking in the concept of cross-validation, in which the real phenotype results measured in this population are compared with the phenotype results based on the prediction, what used to check the accuracy of the model.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] Studies for differential expression of genes from RNA-Seq data, as for RT-qPCR and microarrays, demands comparison of conditions.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] The goal is to identify genes which have a significant change in abundance between different conditions.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] Then, experiments are designed appropriately, with replicates for each condition/treatment, randomization and blocking, when necessary.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] In RNA-Seq, the quantification of expression uses the information of mapped reads that are summarized in some genetic unit, as exons that are part of a gene sequence.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] As microarray results can be approximated by a normal distribution, RNA-Seq counts data are better explained by other distributions.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] The first used distribution was the Poisson one, but it underestimate the sample error, leading to false positives.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] Currently, biological variation is considered by methods that estimate a dispersion parameter of a negative binomial distribution.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] Generalized linear models are used to perform the tests for statistical significance and as the number of genes is high, multiple tests correction have to be considered.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] Some examples of other analysis on genomics data comes from microarray or proteomics experiments.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] Often concerning diseases or disease stages.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] There are a lot of tools that can be used to do statistical analysis in biological data.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] Most of them are useful in other areas of knowledge, covering a large number of applications (alphabetical).
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] Almost all educational programmes in biostatistics are at postgraduate level.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] They are most often found in schools of public health, affiliated with schools of medicine, forestry, or agriculture, or as a focus of application in departments of statistics.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] In the United States, where several universities have dedicated biostatistics departments, many other top-tier universities integrate biostatistics faculty into statistics or other departments, such as epidemiology.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] Thus, departments carrying the name "biostatistics" may exist under quite different structures.
[src:biostatistics/biostatistics] In larger universities around the world, where both a statistics and a biostatistics department exist, the degree of integration between the two departments may range from the bare minimum to very close collaboration.
[src:biostatistics/bonferroni-correction] Statistical hypothesis testing is based on rejecting the null hypothesis when the likelihood of the observed data would be low if the null hypothesis were true.
[src:biostatistics/bonferroni-correction] When multiple hypotheses are tested, the probability of observing a rare event increases, so the likelihood of incorrectly rejecting a null hypothesis (i.e., making a Type I error) increases if multiple null hypotheses are true.
[src:biostatistics/bonferroni-correction] The Bonferroni correction compensates for that increase by testing each individual hypothesis at a significance level of $\alpha /m$ , where $\alpha$ is the desired overall alpha level and m is the number of hypotheses.
[src:biostatistics/bonferroni-correction] For example, if a trial is testing $m=20$ hypotheses with a desired overall $\alpha =0.05$ , the Bonferroni-corrected alpha level would be $\alpha =0.05/20=0.0025$ .
[src:biostatistics/bonferroni-correction] The method is named for its use of the Bonferroni inequalities.
[src:biostatistics/bonferroni-correction] The Bonferroni correction can also be applied as a p-value adjustment: Using that approach, instead of adjusting the alpha level, each p-value is multiplied by the number of tests (with adjusted p-values that exceed 1 then being reduced to 1), and the alpha level is left unchanged.
[src:biostatistics/bonferroni-correction] The significance decisions using this approach will be the same as when using the alpha-level adjustment approach.
[src:biostatistics/bonferroni-correction] Let $H_{1},\ldots ,H_{m}$ be a family of null hypotheses and let $p_{1},\ldots ,p_{m}$ be their corresponding p-values.
[src:biostatistics/bonferroni-correction] Let m be the total number of null hypotheses, and let $m_{0}$ be the number of true null hypotheses (which is presumably unknown to the researcher).
[src:biostatistics/bonferroni-correction] The family-wise error rate (FWER) is the probability of rejecting at least one true $H_{i}$ , that is, of making at least one type I error.
[src:biostatistics/bonferroni-correction] The Bonferroni correction rejects the null hypothesis for each $p_{i}\leq {\frac {\alpha }{m}}$ , thereby controlling the FWER at $\leq \alpha$ .
[src:biostatistics/bonferroni-correction] This control does not require any assumptions about dependence among the p-values or about how many of the null hypotheses are true.
[src:biostatistics/bonferroni-correction] Rather than testing each hypothesis at the $\alpha /m$ level, the hypotheses may be tested at any other combination of levels that add up to $\alpha$ , provided that the level of each test is decided before looking at the data.
[src:biostatistics/bonferroni-correction] For example, for two hypothesis tests, an overall $\alpha$ of 0.05 could be maintained by conducting one test at 0.04 and the other at 0.01.
[src:biostatistics/bonferroni-correction] The procedure proposed by Dunn can be used to adjust confidence intervals.
[src:biostatistics/bonferroni-correction] If one establishes m confidence intervals, and wishes to have an overall confidence level of $1-\alpha$ , each individual confidence interval can be adjusted to the level of $1-{\frac {\alpha }{m}}$ .
[src:biostatistics/bonferroni-correction] When searching for a signal in a continuous parameter space there can also be a problem of multiple comparisons, or look-elsewhere effect.
[src:biostatistics/bonferroni-correction] For example, a physicist might be looking to discover a particle of unknown mass by considering a large range of masses; this was the case during the Nobel Prize winning detection of the Higgs boson.
[src:biostatistics/bonferroni-correction] In such cases, one can apply a continuous generalization of the Bonferroni correction by employing Bayesian logic to relate the effective number of trials, m , to the prior-to-posterior volume ratio.
[src:biostatistics/bonferroni-correction] There are alternative ways to control the family-wise error rate.
[src:biostatistics/bonferroni-correction] For example, the Holm–Bonferroni method and the Šidák correction are universally more powerful procedures than the Bonferroni correction, meaning that they are always at least as powerful.
[src:biostatistics/bonferroni-correction] But unlike the Bonferroni procedure, these methods do not control the expected number of Type I errors per family (the per-family Type I error rate).
[src:biostatistics/bonferroni-correction] With respect to Family-wise error rate (FWER) control, the Bonferroni correction can be conservative if there are a large number of tests and/or the test statistics are positively correlated, due to looseness of the union bound for significantly overlapping sets.
[src:biostatistics/bonferroni-correction] Multiple-testing corrections, including the Bonferroni procedure, increase the probability of Type II errors when null hypotheses are false, i.e., they reduce statistical power.
[src:biostatistics/kaplan-meier-estimator] The **Kaplan–Meier estimator**, also known as the **product limit estimator**, is a non-parametric statistic used to estimate the survival function from lifetime data.
[src:biostatistics/kaplan-meier-estimator] In medical research, it is often used to measure the fraction of patients living for a certain amount of time after treatment.
[src:biostatistics/kaplan-meier-estimator] In other fields, Kaplan–Meier estimators may be used to measure the length of time people remain unemployed after a job loss, the time-to-failure of machine parts, or how long fleshy fruits remain on plants before they are removed by frugivores.
[src:biostatistics/kaplan-meier-estimator] Kaplan and Paul Meier, who each submitted similar manuscripts to the *Journal of the American Statistical Association*.
[src:biostatistics/kaplan-meier-estimator] The journal editor, John Tukey, convinced them to combine their work into one paper, which has been cited more than 34,000 times since its publication in 1958.
[src:biostatistics/kaplan-meier-estimator] with $t_{i}$ a time when at least one event happened, *d**i* the *number of events* (e.g., deaths) that happened at time $t_{i}$ , and $n_{i}$ the *individuals known to have survived* (have not yet had an event or been censored) up to time $t_{i}$ .
[src:biostatistics/kaplan-meier-estimator] A plot of the Kaplan–Meier estimator is a series of declining horizontal steps which, with a large enough sample size, approaches the true survival function for that population.
[src:biostatistics/kaplan-meier-estimator] The value of the survival function between successive distinct sampled observations ("clicks") is assumed to be constant.
[src:biostatistics/kaplan-meier-estimator] An important advantage of the Kaplan–Meier curve is that the method can take into account some types of censored data, particularly *right-censoring*, which occurs if a patient withdraws from a study, is lost to follow-up, or is alive without event occurrence at last follow-up.
[src:biostatistics/kaplan-meier-estimator] On the plot, small vertical tick-marks state individual patients whose survival times have been right-censored.
[src:biostatistics/kaplan-meier-estimator] When no truncation or censoring occurs, the Kaplan–Meier curve is the complement of the empirical distribution function.
[src:biostatistics/kaplan-meier-estimator] In medical statistics, a typical application might involve grouping patients into categories, for instance, those with Gene A profile and those with Gene B profile.
[src:biostatistics/kaplan-meier-estimator] In the graph, patients with Gene B die much quicker than those with Gene A.
[src:biostatistics/kaplan-meier-estimator] After two years, about 80% of the Gene A patients survive, but less than half of patients with Gene B.
[src:biostatistics/kaplan-meier-estimator] To generate a Kaplan–Meier estimator, at least two pieces of data are required for each patient (or each subject): the status at last observation (event occurrence or right-censored), and the time to event (or time to censoring).
[src:biostatistics/kaplan-meier-estimator] If the survival functions between two or more groups are to be compared, then a third piece of data is required: the group assignment of each subject.
[src:biostatistics/kaplan-meier-estimator] Let $\tau \geq 0$ be a random variable as the time that passes between the start of the possible exposure period, $t_{0}$ , and the time that the event of interest takes place, $t_{1}$ .
[src:biostatistics/kaplan-meier-estimator] As indicated above, the goal is to estimate the survival function S underlying $\tau$ .
[src:biostatistics/kaplan-meier-estimator] Let $\tau _{1},\dots ,\tau _{n}\geq 0$ be independent, identically distributed random variables, whose common distribution is that of $\tau$ : $\tau _{j}$ is the random time when some event j happened.
[src:biostatistics/kaplan-meier-estimator] In particular, the information available about the timing of event j is whether the event happened before the fixed time $c_{j}$ and if so, then the actual time of the event is also available.
[src:biostatistics/kaplan-meier-estimator] The challenge is to estimate $S(t)$ given this data.
[src:biostatistics/kaplan-meier-estimator] Two derivations of the Kaplan–Meier estimator are shown.
[src:biostatistics/kaplan-meier-estimator] Both are based on rewriting the survival function in terms of what is sometimes called **hazard**, or **mortality rates**.
[src:biostatistics/kaplan-meier-estimator] However, before doing this it is worthwhile to consider a naive estimator.
[src:biostatistics/kaplan-meier-estimator] To understand the power of the Kaplan–Meier estimator, it is worthwhile to first describe a naive estimator of the survival function.
[src:biostatistics/kaplan-meier-estimator] Let $X_{k}=\mathbb {I} ({\tilde {\tau }}_{k}\geq t)$ and consider only those $k\in C(t):=\{k\,:\,c_{k}\geq t\}$ , i.e. the events for which the outcome was not censored before time t .
[src:biostatistics/kaplan-meier-estimator] Let $m(t)=|C(t)|$ be the number of elements in $C(t)$ .
[src:biostatistics/kaplan-meier-estimator] Note that the set $C(t)$ is not random and so neither is $m(t)$ .
[src:biostatistics/kaplan-meier-estimator] Furthermore, $(X_{k})_{k\in C(t)}$ is a sequence of independent, identically distributed Bernoulli random variables with common parameter $S(t)=\operatorname {Prob} (\tau \geq t)$ .
[src:biostatistics/kaplan-meier-estimator] where the second equality follows because ${\tilde {\tau }}_{k}\geq t$ implies $c_{k}\geq t$ , while the last equality is simply a change of notation.
[src:biostatistics/kaplan-meier-estimator] The quality of this estimate is governed by the size of $m(t)$ .
[src:biostatistics/kaplan-meier-estimator] This can be problematic when $m(t)$ is small, which happens, by definition, when a lot of the events are censored.
[src:biostatistics/kaplan-meier-estimator] A particularly unpleasant property of this estimator, that suggests that perhaps it is not the "best" estimator, is that it ignores all the observations whose censoring time precedes t .
[src:biostatistics/kaplan-meier-estimator] However, this information is ignored by this naive estimator.
[src:biostatistics/kaplan-meier-estimator] The question is then whether there exists an estimator that makes a better use of all the data.
[src:biostatistics/kaplan-meier-estimator] This is what the Kaplan–Meier estimator accomplishes.
[src:biostatistics/kaplan-meier-estimator] Note that the naive estimator cannot be improved when censoring does not take place; so whether an improvement is possible critically hinges upon whether censoring is in place.
[src:biostatistics/kaplan-meier-estimator] The Kaplan–Meier estimator can be seen as a "plug-in estimator" where each $q(s)$ is estimated based on the data and the estimator of $S(t)$ is obtained as a product of these estimates.
[src:biostatistics/kaplan-meier-estimator] It remains to specify how $q(s)=1-\operatorname {Prob} (\tau =s\mid \tau \geq s)$ is to be estimated.
[src:biostatistics/kaplan-meier-estimator] (think of estimating the numerator and denominator separately in the definition of the "hazard rate" $\operatorname {Prob} (\tau =s|\tau \geq s)$ ).
[src:biostatistics/kaplan-meier-estimator] The form of the estimator stated at the beginning of the article can be obtained by some further algebra.
[src:biostatistics/kaplan-meier-estimator] This implies that we can leave out from the product defining ${\hat {S}}(t)$ all those terms where $d(s)=0$ .
[src:biostatistics/kaplan-meier-estimator] Kaplan–Meier estimator can be derived from maximum likelihood estimation of the discrete hazard function.
[src:biostatistics/kaplan-meier-estimator] More specifically given $d_{i}$ as the number of events and $n_{i}$ the total individuals at risk at time $t_{i}$ , discrete hazard rate $h_{i}$ can be defined as the probability of an individual with an event at time $t_{i}$ .
[src:biostatistics/kaplan-meier-estimator] where hat is used to denote maximum likelihood estimation.
[src:biostatistics/kaplan-meier-estimator] More generally (for continuous as well as discrete survival distributions), the Kaplan-Meier estimator may be interpreted as a nonparametric maximum likelihood estimator.
[src:biostatistics/kaplan-meier-estimator] The Kaplan–Meier estimator is one of the most frequently used methods of survival analysis.
[src:biostatistics/kaplan-meier-estimator] The estimate may be useful to examine recovery rates, the probability of death, and the effectiveness of treatment.
[src:biostatistics/kaplan-meier-estimator] It is limited in its ability to estimate survival adjusted for covariates; parametric survival models and the Cox proportional hazards model may be useful to estimate covariate-adjusted survival.
[src:biostatistics/kaplan-meier-estimator] The Kaplan-Meier estimator is directly related to the Nelson-Aalen estimator and both maximize the empirical likelihood.
[src:biostatistics/kaplan-meier-estimator] The Kaplan–Meier estimator is a statistic, and several estimators are used to approximate its variance.
[src:biostatistics/kaplan-meier-estimator] where $d_{i}$ is the number of cases and $n_{i}$ is the total number of observations, for $t_{i}<t$ .
[src:biostatistics/kaplan-meier-estimator] Greenwood's formula is derived by noting that probability of getting $d_{i}$ failures out of $n_{i}$ cases follows a binomial distribution with failure probability $h_{i}$ .
[src:biostatistics/kaplan-meier-estimator] In some cases, one may wish to compare different Kaplan–Meier curves.
[src:biostatistics/kaplan-meier-estimator] This can be done by the log rank test, and the Cox proportional hazards test.
[src:biostatistics/kaplan-meier-estimator] Other statistics that may be of use with this estimator are pointwise confidence intervals, the Hall-Wellner band and the equal-precision band.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] In null-hypothesis significance testing, the ***p*-value** is the probability of obtaining test results at least as extreme as the result actually observed, under the assumption that the null hypothesis is correct.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] A very small *p*-value means that such an extreme observed outcome would be very unlikely *under the null hypothesis*.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] Even though reporting *p*-values of statistical tests is common practice in academic publications of many quantitative fields, misinterpretation and misuse of p-values is widespread and has been a major topic in mathematics and metascience.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] That said, a 2019 task force by ASA has issued a statement on statistical significance and replicability, concluding with: "*p*-values and significance tests, when properly applied and interpreted, increase the rigor of the conclusions drawn from data".
[src:biostatistics/p-value] In statistics, every conjecture concerning the unknown probability distribution of a collection of random variables representing the observed data X in some study is called a *statistical hypothesis*.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] If we state one hypothesis only and the aim of the statistical test is to see whether this hypothesis is tenable, but not to investigate other specific hypotheses, then such a test is called a null hypothesis test.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] As our statistical hypothesis will, by definition, state some property of the distribution, the null hypothesis is the default hypothesis under which that property does not exist.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] The null hypothesis is typically that some parameter (such as a correlation or a difference between means) in the populations of interest is zero.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] Our hypothesis might specify the probability distribution of X precisely, or it might only specify that it belongs to some class of distributions.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] Often, we reduce the data to a single numerical statistic, e.g., T , whose marginal probability distribution is closely connected to a main question of interest in the study.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] The *p*-value is used in the context of null hypothesis testing in order to quantify the statistical significance of a result, the result being the observed value of the chosen statistic T .
[src:biostatistics/p-value] The lower the *p*-value is, the lower the probability of getting that result if the null hypothesis were true.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] A result is said to be *statistically significant* if it allows us to reject the null hypothesis.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] All other things being equal, smaller *p*-values are taken as stronger evidence against the null hypothesis.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] Loosely speaking, rejection of the null hypothesis implies that there is sufficient evidence against it.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] Different tests of the same null hypothesis would be more or less sensitive to different alternatives.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] However, even if we do manage to reject the null hypothesis for all 3 alternatives, and even if we know that the distribution is normal and variance is 1, the null hypothesis test does not tell us which non-zero values of the mean are now most plausible.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] The *p*-value is the probability under the null hypothesis of obtaining a real-valued test statistic at least as extreme as the one obtained.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] Consider an observed test-statistic t from unknown distribution T .
[src:biostatistics/p-value] Then the *p*-value p is what the prior probability would be of observing a test-statistic value at least as "extreme" as t if null hypothesis $H_{0}$ were true.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] The 0.05 value (equivalent to 1/20 chances) was originally proposed by Ronald Fisher in 1925 in his famous book entitled "Statistical Methods for Research Workers".
[src:biostatistics/p-value] Different *p*-values based on independent sets of data can be combined, for instance using Fisher's combined probability test.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] The *p*-value is a function of the chosen test statistic T and is therefore a random variable.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] If the null hypothesis fixes the probability distribution of T precisely (e.g. $H_{0}:\theta =\theta _{0},$ where $\theta$ is the only parameter), and if that distribution is continuous, then when the null-hypothesis is true, the *p*-value is uniformly distributed between 0 and 1.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] Regardless of the truth of the $H_{0}$ , the *p*-value is not fixed; if the same test is repeated independently with fresh data, one will typically obtain a different *p*-value in each iteration.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] Usually only a single *p*-value relating to a hypothesis is observed, so the *p*-value is interpreted by a significance test, and no effort is made to estimate the distribution it was drawn from.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] When a collection of *p*-values are available (e.g. when considering a group of studies on the same subject), the distribution of significant *p*-values is sometimes called a *p*-curve.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] A *p*-curve can be used to assess the reliability of scientific literature, such as by detecting publication bias or *p*-hacking.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] In parametric hypothesis testing problems, a *simple or point hypothesis* refers to a hypothesis where the parameter's value is assumed to be a single number.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] In contrast, in a *composite hypothesis* the parameter's value is given by a set of numbers.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] When the null-hypothesis is composite (or the distribution of the statistic is discrete), then when the null-hypothesis is true the probability of obtaining a *p*-value less than or equal to any number between 0 and 1 is still less than or equal to that number.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] In other words, it remains the case that very small values are relatively unlikely if the null-hypothesis is true, and that a significance test at level $\alpha$ is obtained by rejecting the null-hypothesis if the *p*-value is less than or equal to $\alpha$ .
[src:biostatistics/p-value] In this example, that would be the *Z*-statistic belonging to the one-sided one-sample *Z*-test.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] For each possible value of the theoretical mean, the *Z*-test statistic has a different probability distribution.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] In these circumstances, the *p*-value is defined by taking the least favorable null-hypothesis case, which is typically on the border between null and alternative.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] This definition ensures the complementarity of p-values and alpha-levels: $\alpha =0.05$ means one only rejects the null hypothesis if the *p*-value is less than or equal to $0.05$ , and the hypothesis test will indeed have a *maximum* type-1 error rate of $0.05$ .
[src:biostatistics/p-value] The *p*-value is widely used in statistical hypothesis testing, specifically in null hypothesis significance testing.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] In this method, before conducting the study, one first chooses a model (the null hypothesis) and the alpha level *α* (most commonly 0.05).
[src:biostatistics/p-value] After analyzing the data, if the *p*-value is less than *α*, that is taken to mean that the observed data is sufficiently inconsistent with the null hypothesis for the null hypothesis to be rejected.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] However, that does not prove that the null hypothesis is false.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] The *p*-value does not, in itself, establish probabilities of hypotheses.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] Rather, it is a tool for deciding whether to reject the null hypothesis.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] According to the ASA, there is widespread agreement that *p*-values are often misused and misinterpreted.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] One practice that has been particularly criticized is accepting the alternative hypothesis for any *p*-value nominally less than 0.05 without other supporting evidence.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] Another concern is that the *p*-value is often misunderstood as being the probability that the null hypothesis is true.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] *p*-values and significance tests also say nothing about the possibility of drawing conclusions from a sample to a population.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] Some statisticians have proposed abandoning *p*-values and focusing more on other inferential statistics, such as confidence intervals, likelihood ratios, or Bayes factors, but there is heated debate on the feasibility of these alternatives.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] At the same time, the use of *p*-values has also been defended as a useful statistical tool that should not be abandoned.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] Others have suggested to remove fixed significance thresholds and to interpret *p*-values as continuous indices of the strength of evidence against the null hypothesis, although these proposals in themselves have been criticized.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] Yet others suggested to report alongside *p*-values the prior probability of a real effect that would be required to obtain a false positive risk (i.e. the probability that there is no real effect) below a pre-specified threshold (e.g.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] That said, in 2019 a task force by ASA had convened to consider the use of statistical methods in scientific studies, specifically hypothesis tests and *p*-values, and their connection to replicability.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] It states that "Different measures of uncertainty can complement one another; no single measure serves all purposes", citing *p*-value as one of these measures.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] They also stress that *p*-values can provide valuable information when considering the specific value as well as when compared to some threshold.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] In general, it stresses that "*p*-values and significance tests, when properly applied and interpreted, increase the rigor of the conclusions drawn from data".
[src:biostatistics/p-value] A test statistic is the output of a scalar function of all the observations.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] This statistic provides a single number, such as a *t*-statistic or an *F*-statistic.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] As such, the test statistic follows a distribution determined by the function used to define that test statistic and the distribution of the input observational data.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] For the important case in which the data are hypothesized to be a random sample from a normal distribution, depending on the nature of the test statistic and the hypotheses of interest about its distribution, different null hypothesis tests have been developed.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] Thus computing a *p*-value requires a null hypothesis, a test statistic (together with deciding whether the researcher is performing a one-tailed test or a two-tailed test), and data.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] Even though computing the test statistic on given data may be easy, computing the sampling distribution under the null hypothesis, and then computing its cumulative distribution function (CDF) is often a difficult problem.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] Today, this computation is done using statistical software, often via numeric methods (rather than exact formulae), but, in the early and mid 20th century, this was instead done via tables of values, and one interpolated or extrapolated *p*-values from these discrete values.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] Rather than using a table of *p*-values, Fisher instead inverted the CDF, publishing a list of values of the test statistic for given fixed *p*-values; this corresponds to computing the quantile function (inverse CDF).
[src:biostatistics/p-value] As an example of a statistical test, an experiment is performed to determine whether a coin flip is fair (equal chance of landing heads or tails) or unfairly biased (one outcome being more likely than the other).
[src:biostatistics/p-value] Suppose that the experimental results show the coin turning up heads 14 times out of 20 total flips.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] The full data X would be a sequence of twenty times the symbol "H" or "T".
[src:biostatistics/p-value] The statistic on which one might focus could be the total number T of heads.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] The null hypothesis is that the coin is fair, and coin tosses are independent of one another.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] If a right-tailed test is considered, which would be the case if one is actually interested in the possibility that the coin is biased towards falling heads, then the *p*-value of this result is the chance of a fair coin landing on heads *at least* 14 times out of 20 flips.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] This probability is the *p*-value, considering only extreme results that favor heads.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] However, one might be interested in deviations in either direction, favoring either heads or tails.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] The two-tailed *p*-value, which considers deviations favoring either heads or tails, may instead be calculated.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] As the binomial distribution is symmetrical for a fair coin, the two-sided *p*-value is simply twice the above calculated single-sided *p*-value: the two-sided *p*-value is 0.115.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] The Pr(no. of heads ≤ 14 heads) = 1 − Pr(no. of heads ≥ 14 heads) + Pr(no. of head = 14) = 1 − 0.058 + 0.036 = 0.978; however, the symmetry of this binomial distribution makes it an unnecessary computation to find the smaller of the two probabilities.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] Here, the calculated *p*-value exceeds 0.05, meaning that the data falls within the range of what would happen 95% of the time, if the coin were fair.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] Hence, the null hypothesis is not rejected at the 0.05 level.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] However, had one more head been obtained, the resulting *p*-value (two-tailed) would have been 0.0414 (4.14%), in which case the null hypothesis would be rejected at the 0.05 level.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] The difference between the two meanings of "extreme" appear when we consider a sequential hypothesis testing, or optional stopping, for the fairness of the coin.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] In general, optional stopping changes how p-value is calculated.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] This experiment has 7 types of outcomes: 2 heads, 2 tails, 5 heads 1 tail, ..., 1 head 5 tails.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] We now calculate the *p*-value of the "3 heads 3 tails" outcome.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] If we use the test statistic # ${\text{heads}}/{\text{tails}}$ , then under the null hypothesis (i.e. # ${\text{heads}}\leq 3$ ) the two-sided *p*-value is exactly equal to 1, and both the one-sided left-tail p-value and the one-sided right-tail *p*-value are exactly equal to $19/32$ .
[src:biostatistics/p-value] However, suppose we have planned to simply flip the coin 6 times no matter what happens, then the second definition of *p*-value would mean that the *p*-value of "3 heads 3 tails" is exactly 1.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] Thus, the "at least as extreme" definition of *p*-value is deeply contextual and depends on what the experimenter *planned* to do even in situations that did not occur.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] The *p*-value was first formally introduced by Karl Pearson, in his Pearson's chi-squared test, using the chi-squared distribution and notated as capital P.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] The *p*-values for the chi-squared distribution (for various values of χ2 and degrees of freedom), now notated as *P,* were calculated in (Elderton 1902), collected in (Pearson 1914, pp. xxxi–xxxiii, 26–28, Table XII).
[src:biostatistics/p-value] Ronald Fisher formalized and popularized the use of the *p*-value in statistics, with it playing a central role in his approach to the subject.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] That allowed computed values of χ2 to be compared against cutoffs and encouraged the use of *p*-values (especially 0.05, 0.02, and 0.01) as cutoffs, instead of computing and reporting *p*-values themselves.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] The same type of tables were then compiled in (Fisher & Yates 1938), which cemented the approach.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] As an illustration of the application of *p*-values to the design and interpretation of experiments, in his following book *The Design of Experiments* (1935), Fisher presented the lady tasting tea experiment, which is the archetypal example of the *p*-value.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] He also applies this threshold to the design of experiments, noting that had only 6 cups been presented (3 of each), a perfect classification would have only yielded a *p*-value of $1/{\binom {6}{3}}=1/20=0.05,$ which would not have met this level of significance.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] Fisher also underlined the interpretation of *p,* as the long-run proportion of values at least as extreme as the data, assuming the null hypothesis is true.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] In later editions, Fisher explicitly contrasted the use of the *p*-value for statistical inference in science with the Neyman–Pearson method, which he terms "Acceptance Procedures".
[src:biostatistics/p-value] Fisher emphasizes that while fixed levels such as 5%, 2%, and 1% are convenient, the exact *p*-value can be used, and the strength of evidence can and will be revised with further experimentation.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] In contrast, decision procedures require a clear-cut decision, yielding an irreversible action, and the procedure is based on costs of error, which, he argues, are inapplicable to scientific research.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] The *E-value* can refer to two concepts, both of which are related to the p-value and both of which play a role in multiple testing.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] First, it corresponds to a generic, more robust alternative to the p-value that can deal with *optional continuation* of experiments.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] Second, it is also used to abbreviate "expect value", which is the expected number of times that one expects to obtain a test statistic at least as extreme as the one that was actually observed if one assumes that the null hypothesis is true.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] This expect-value is the product of the number of tests and the *p*-value.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] The *q*-value is the analog of the *p*-value with respect to the positive false discovery rate.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] It is used in multiple hypothesis testing to maintain statistical power while minimizing the false positive rate.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] The Probability of Direction (*pd*) is the Bayesian numerical equivalent of the *p*-value.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] It corresponds to the proportion of the posterior distribution that is of the median's sign, typically varying between 50% and 100%, and representing the certainty with which an effect is positive or negative.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] Second-generation p-values extend the concept of p-values by not considering extremely small, practically irrelevant effect sizes as significant.
[src:biostatistics/p-value] The S-value, also known as the surprisal value, has been defined as a logarithmic transformation of the p-value: S-value = - log2(p-value).
[src:biostatistics/p-value] The transformation into S-values is intended to facilitate the interpretation of p-values by using a more intuitive logarithmic scale that indicates how “surprised” one is by a result.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] A **statistical hypothesis test** is a method of statistical inference used to decide whether the data provide sufficient evidence to reject a particular hypothesis.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] A statistical hypothesis test typically involves a calculation of a test statistic.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Then a decision is made, either by comparing the test statistic to a critical value or equivalently by evaluating a *p*-value computed from the test statistic.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Roughly 100 specialized statistical tests are in use.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] The goal of a hypothesis test is to establish whether certain properties of a statistical population are true by examining sample data.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Typically, the population is modelled by a random variable whose distribution has unknown parameters.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] For example, a medical trial may wish to establish whether a particular drug is effective in treating high blood pressure, with "the change in blood pressure observed in a patient who takes the drug" being the random variable.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] An example hypothesis could be "the mean change in blood pressure is zero" or "the mean change in blood pressure is negative".
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] In general, any statement about the parameters describing a **population** can be a hypothesis (but not a statement about the sample).
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] The test compares two hypotheses: a default "null" hypothesis (denoted H0) and its negation, the "alternative" hypothesis (H1).
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Typically the test will select a null hypothesis that the intervention being studied has no effect, or that the population parameter takes some "obvious" value.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] A test statistic is computed from the given sample data, and the tester calculates the conditional probability of observing a value at least this extreme, supposing the null hypothesis is true.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] If this probability (called the p-value) is less than the significance level of the test (denoted $\alpha$ ), then the null hypothesis is rejected.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] The test does **not** conclude that the null hypothesis is false, or that the probability that the null hypothesis is false is less than $\alpha$ .
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Because it is usually impossible to definitely establish whether the hypothesis being tested is true or false from a sample, the conclusion of a hypothesis test is not certain to be correct.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] A statistical hypothesis test compares a test statistic (*z* or *t* for examples) to a threshold.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] The test statistic (the formula found in the table below) is based on optimality.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] For a fixed level of Type I error rate, use of these statistics minimizes Type II error rates (equivalent to maximizing power).
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] While hypothesis testing was popularized early in the 20th century, early forms were used in the 1700s.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] The first use is credited to John Arbuthnot (1710), followed by Pierre-Simon Laplace (1770s), in analyzing the human sex ratio at birth; see § Human sex ratio.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Ronald Fisher began his life in statistics as a Bayesian (Zabell 1992), but Fisher soon grew disenchanted with the subjectivity involved (namely use of the principle of indifference when determining prior probabilities), and sought to provide a more "objective" approach to inductive inference.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Fisher emphasized rigorous experimental design and methods to extract a result from few samples assuming Gaussian distributions.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Neyman (who teamed with the younger Pearson) emphasized mathematical rigor and methods to obtain more results from many samples and a wider range of distributions.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Modern hypothesis testing is an inconsistent hybrid of the Fisher vs Neyman/Pearson formulation, methods and terminology developed in the early 20th century.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Fisher popularized the "significance test".
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] He required a null-hypothesis (corresponding to a population frequency distribution) and a sample.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] His (now familiar) calculations determined whether to reject the null-hypothesis or not.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Significance testing did not utilize an alternative hypothesis so there was no concept of a Type II error (false negative).
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] The *p*-value was devised as an informal, but objective, index meant to help a researcher determine (based on other knowledge) whether to modify future experiments or strengthen one's faith in the null hypothesis.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Hypothesis testing (and Type I/II errors) was devised by Neyman and Pearson as a more objective alternative to Fisher's *p*-value, also meant to determine researcher behaviour, but without requiring any inductive inference by the researcher.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Neyman & Pearson considered a different problem to Fisher (which they called "hypothesis testing").
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] They initially considered two simple hypotheses (both with frequency distributions).
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] They calculated two probabilities and typically selected the hypothesis associated with the higher probability (the hypothesis more likely to have generated the sample).
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Their method always selected a hypothesis.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] It also allowed the calculation of both types of error probabilities.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Fisher and Neyman/Pearson clashed bitterly.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Neyman/Pearson considered their formulation to be an improved generalization of significance testing (the defining paper was abstract; Mathematicians have generalized and refined the theory for decades).
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Fisher thought that it was not applicable to scientific research because often, during the course of the experiment, it is discovered that the initial assumptions about the null hypothesis are questionable due to unexpected sources of error.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] He believed that the use of rigid reject/accept decisions based on models formulated before data is collected was incompatible with this common scenario faced by scientists and attempts to apply this method to scientific research would lead to mass confusion.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] The dispute between Fisher and Neyman–Pearson was waged on philosophical grounds, characterized by a philosopher as a dispute over the proper role of models in statistical inference.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Neyman accepted a position in the University of California, Berkeley in 1938, breaking his partnership with Pearson and separating the disputants (who had previously occupied the same building).
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] The dispute between Fisher and Neyman terminated (unresolved after 27 years) with Fisher's death in 1962.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Some of Neyman's later publications reported *p*-values and significance levels.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] The modern version of hypothesis testing is generally called the **null hypothesis significance testing (NHST)** and is a hybrid of the Fisher approach with the Neyman-Pearson approach.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Nickerson wrote an article stating that NHST was (at the time) "arguably the most widely used method of analysis of data collected in psychological experiments and has been so for about 70 years" and that it was at the same time "very controversial".
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] This fusion resulted from confusion by writers of statistical textbooks (as predicted by Fisher) beginning in the 1940s (but signal detection, for example, still uses the Neyman/Pearson formulation).
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Great conceptual differences and many caveats in addition to those mentioned above were ignored.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Neyman and Pearson provided the stronger terminology, the more rigorous mathematics and the more consistent philosophy, but the subject taught today in introductory statistics has more similarities with Fisher's method than theirs.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Sometime around 1940, authors of statistical text books began combining the two approaches by using the *p*-value in place of the test statistic (or data) to test against the Neyman–Pearson "significance level".
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Paul Meehl has argued that the epistemological importance of the choice of null hypothesis has gone largely unacknowledged.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] When the null hypothesis is predicted by theory, a more precise experiment will be a more severe test of the underlying theory.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] When the null hypothesis defaults to "no difference" or "no effect", a more precise experiment is a less severe test of the theory that motivated performing the experiment.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Fisher and Neyman opposed the subjectivity of probability.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Their views contributed to the objective definitions.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] The core of their historical disagreement was philosophical.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Many of the philosophical criticisms of hypothesis testing are discussed by statisticians in other contexts, particularly correlation does not imply causation and the design of experiments.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Hypothesis testing is of continuing interest to philosophers.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Statistics is increasingly being taught in schools with hypothesis testing being one of the elements taught.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Many conclusions reported in the popular press (political opinion polls to medical studies) are based on statistics.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] An introductory college statistics class places much emphasis on hypothesis testing – perhaps half of the course.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Such fields as literature and divinity now include findings based on statistical analysis (see the Bible Analyzer).
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] An introductory statistics class teaches hypothesis testing as a cookbook process.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Hypothesis testing is also taught at the postgraduate level.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Statisticians learn how to create good statistical test procedures (like *z*, Student's *t*, *F* and chi-squared).
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Statistical hypothesis testing is considered a mature area within statistics, but a limited amount of development continues.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] An academic study states that the cookbook method of teaching introductory statistics leaves no time for history, philosophy or controversy.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Hypothesis testing has been taught as received unified method.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Surveys showed that graduates of the class were filled with philosophical misconceptions (on all aspects of statistical inference) that persisted among instructors.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] While the problem was addressed more than a decade ago, and calls for educational reform continue, students still graduate from statistics classes holding fundamental misconceptions about hypothesis testing.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Ideas for improving the teaching of hypothesis testing include encouraging students to search for statistical errors in published papers, teaching the history of statistics and emphasizing the controversy in a generally dry subject.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Select a relevant statistical test with associated test statistic *T*.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Derive the distribution of the test statistic under the null hypothesis from the assumptions.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] In standard cases this will be a well-known result.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] For example, the test statistic might follow a Student's t distribution with known degrees of freedom, or a normal distribution with known mean and variance.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Select a significance level (*α*), the maximum acceptable false positive rate.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Compute from the observations the observed value *t*obs of the test statistic *T*.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Decide to either reject the null hypothesis in favor of the alternative or not reject it.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] The Neyman-Pearson decision rule is to reject the null hypothesis *H*0 if the observed value *t*obs is in the critical region, and not to reject the null hypothesis otherwise.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] The former report is adequate, the latter gives a more detailed explanation of the data and the reason why the suitcase is being checked.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Not rejecting the null hypothesis does not mean the null hypothesis is "accepted" per se (though Neyman and Pearson used that word in their original writings; see the Interpretation section).
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] The processes described here are perfectly adequate for computation.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] They seriously neglect the design of experiments considerations.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] It is particularly critical that appropriate sample sizes be estimated before conducting the experiment.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] The phrase "test of significance" was coined by statistician Ronald Fisher.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] When the null hypothesis is true and statistical assumptions are met, the probability that the p-value will be less than or equal to the significance level $\alpha$ is at most $\alpha$ .
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] This ensures that the hypothesis test maintains its specified false positive rate (provided that statistical assumptions are met).
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] The *p*-value is the probability that a test statistic which is at least as extreme as the one obtained would occur under the null hypothesis.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] At a significance level of 0.05, a fair coin would be expected to (incorrectly) reject the null hypothesis (that it is fair) in 1 out of 20 tests on average.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] The *p*-value does not provide the probability that either the null hypothesis or its opposite is correct (a common source of confusion).
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] If the *p*-value is less than the chosen significance threshold (equivalently, if the observed test statistic is in the critical region), then we say the null hypothesis is rejected at the chosen level of significance.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] If the *p*-value is *not* less than the chosen significance threshold (equivalently, if the observed test statistic is outside the critical region), then the null hypothesis is not rejected at the chosen level of significance.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] In the "lady tasting tea" example (below), Fisher required the lady to properly categorize all of the cups of tea to justify the conclusion that the result was unlikely to result from chance.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] His test revealed that if the lady was effectively guessing at random (the null hypothesis), there was a 1.4% chance that the observed results (perfectly ordered tea) would occur.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Statistics are helpful in analyzing most collections of data.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] This is equally true of hypothesis testing which can justify conclusions even when no scientific theory exists.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] In the Lady tasting tea example, it was "obvious" that no difference existed between (milk poured into tea) and (tea poured into milk).
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Statistical hypothesis testing plays an important role in the whole of statistics and in statistical inference.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Significance testing has been the favored statistical tool in some experimental social sciences (over 90% of articles in the *Journal of Applied Psychology* during the early 1990s).
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Other fields have favored the estimation of parameters (e.g. effect size).
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Significance testing is used as a substitute for the traditional comparison of predicted value and experimental result at the core of the scientific method.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] When theory is only capable of predicting the sign of a relationship, a directional (one-sided) hypothesis test can be configured so that only a statistically significant result supports theory.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] This form of theory appraisal is the most heavily criticized application of hypothesis testing.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] "If the government required statistical procedures to carry warning labels like those on drugs, most inference methods would have long labels indeed." This caution applies to hypothesis tests and alternatives to them.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] The successful hypothesis test is associated with a probability and a type-I error rate.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] The conclusion of the test is only as solid as the sample upon which it is based.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] The design of the experiment is critical.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] A statistical analysis of misleading data produces misleading conclusions.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] The issue of data quality can be more subtle.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] In forecasting for example, there is no agreement on a measure of forecast accuracy.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] In the absence of a consensus measurement, no decision based on measurements will be without controversy.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Publication bias: Statistically nonsignificant results may be less likely to be published, which can bias the literature.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Multiple testing: When multiple true null hypothesis tests are conducted at once without adjustment, the overall probability of Type I error is higher than the nominal alpha level.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Those making critical decisions based on the results of a hypothesis test are prudent to look at the details rather than the conclusion alone.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] In the physical sciences most results are fully accepted only when independently confirmed.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Bootstrap-based resampling methods can be used for null hypothesis testing.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] A bootstrap creates numerous simulated samples by randomly resampling (with replacement) the original, combined sample data, assuming the null hypothesis is correct.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] The bootstrap is very versatile as it is distribution-free and it does not rely on restrictive parametric assumptions, but rather on empirical approximate methods with asymptotic guarantees.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Traditional parametric hypothesis tests are more computationally efficient but make stronger structural assumptions.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] In situations where computing the probability of the test statistic under the null hypothesis is hard or impossible (due to perhaps inconvenience or lack of knowledge of the underlying distribution), the bootstrap offers a viable method for statistical inference.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] The earliest use of statistical hypothesis testing is generally credited to the question of whether male and female births are equally likely (null hypothesis), which was addressed in the 1700s by John Arbuthnot (1710), and later by Pierre-Simon Laplace (1770s).
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Arbuthnot examined birth records in London for each of the 82 years from 1629 to 1710, and applied the sign test, a simple non-parametric test.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] In every year, the number of males born in London exceeded the number of females.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Considering more male or more female births as equally likely, the probability of the observed outcome is 0.582, or about 1 in 4,836,000,000,000,000,000,000,000; in modern terms, this is the *p*-value.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Laplace considered the statistics of almost half a million births.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] The statistics showed an excess of boys compared to girls.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] He concluded by calculation of a *p*-value that the excess was a real, but unexplained, effect.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] In a famous example of hypothesis testing, known as the *Lady tasting tea*, Dr.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Muriel Bristol, a colleague of Fisher, claimed to be able to tell whether the tea or the milk was added first to a cup.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Fisher proposed to give her eight cups, four of each variety, in random order.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] One could then ask what the probability was for her getting the number she got correct, but just by chance.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] The null hypothesis was that the Lady had no such ability.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] The test statistic was a simple count of the number of successes in selecting the four cups.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] The critical region was the single case of 4 successes of 4 possible based on a conventional probability criterion (< 5%).
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] A pattern of 4 successes corresponds to 1 out of 70 possible combinations (p≈ 1.4%).
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Fisher asserted that no alternative hypothesis was (ever) required.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] The lady correctly identified every cup, which would be considered a statistically significant result.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] A person (the subject) is tested for clairvoyance.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] They are shown the back face of a randomly chosen playing card 25 times and asked which of the four suits it belongs to.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] The number of hits, or correct answers, is called *X*.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] As we try to find evidence of their clairvoyance, for the time being the null hypothesis is that the person is not clairvoyant.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] The alternative is: the person is (more or less) clairvoyant.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] If the null hypothesis is valid, the only thing the test person can do is guess.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] For every card, the probability (relative frequency) of any single suit appearing is 1/4.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] If the alternative is valid, the test subject will predict the suit correctly with probability greater than 1/4.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] We will call the probability of guessing correctly *p*.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] When the test subject correctly predicts all 25 cards, we will consider them clairvoyant, and reject the null hypothesis.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] With only 5 or 6 hits, on the other hand, there is no cause to consider them so.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] What is the critical number, *c*, of hits, at which point we consider the subject to be clairvoyant?
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] How do we determine the critical value *c*?
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] With the choice *c*=25 (i.e. we only accept clairvoyance when all cards are predicted correctly) we're more critical than with *c*=10.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] In the first case almost no test subjects will be recognized to be clairvoyant, in the second case, a certain number will pass the test.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] In practice, one decides how critical one will be.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] That is, one decides how often one accepts an error of the first kind – a false positive, or Type I error.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] The probability of a false positive is the probability of randomly guessing correctly all 25 times.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Thus, *c* = 10 yields a much greater probability of false positive.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Before the test is actually performed, the maximum acceptable probability of a Type I error (*α*) is determined.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Typically, values in the range of 1% to 5% are selected.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] (If the maximum acceptable error rate is zero, an infinite number of correct guesses is required.) Depending on this Type 1 error rate, the critical value *c* is calculated.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] From all the numbers c, with this property, we choose the smallest, in order to minimize the probability of a Type II error, a false negative.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] For the above example, we select: $c=13$ .
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Statistical hypothesis testing is a key technique of both frequentist inference and Bayesian inference, although the two types of inference have notable differences.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Statistical hypothesis tests define a procedure that controls (fixes) the probability of incorrectly *deciding* that a default position (null hypothesis) is incorrect.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] The procedure is based on how likely it would be for a set of observations to occur if the null hypothesis were true.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] This probability of making an incorrect decision is *not* the probability that the null hypothesis is true, nor whether any specific alternative hypothesis is true.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] This contrasts with other possible techniques of decision theory in which the null and alternative hypothesis are treated on a more equal basis.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] One naïve Bayesian approach to hypothesis testing is to base decisions on the posterior probability, but this fails when comparing point and continuous hypotheses.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Other approaches to decision making, such as Bayesian decision theory, attempt to balance the consequences of incorrect decisions across all possibilities, rather than concentrating on a single null hypothesis.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] A number of other approaches to reaching a decision based on data are available via decision theory and optimal decisions, some of which have desirable properties.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Hypothesis testing, though, is a dominant approach to data analysis in many fields of science.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Extensions to the theory of hypothesis testing include the study of the power of tests, i.e. the probability of correctly rejecting the null hypothesis given that it is false.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Such considerations can be used for the purpose of sample size determination prior to the collection of data.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] An example of Neyman–Pearson hypothesis testing (or null hypothesis statistical significance testing) can be made by a change to the radioactive suitcase example.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] If the "suitcase" is actually a shielded container for the transportation of radioactive material, then a test might be used to select among three hypotheses: no radioactive source present, one present, two (all) present.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] The test could be required for safety, with actions required in each case.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] The Neyman–Pearson lemma of hypothesis testing says that a good criterion for the selection of hypotheses is the ratio of their probabilities (a likelihood ratio).
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] A simple method of solution is to select the hypothesis with the highest probability for the Geiger counts observed.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] The typical result matches intuition: few counts imply no source, many counts imply two sources and intermediate counts imply one source.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Notice also that usually there are problems for proving a negative.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Null hypotheses should be at least falsifiable.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Neyman–Pearson theory can accommodate both prior probabilities and the costs of actions resulting from decisions.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] The former allows each test to consider the results of earlier tests (unlike Fisher's significance tests).
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] The latter allows the consideration of economic issues (for example) as well as probabilities.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] A likelihood ratio remains a good criterion for selecting among hypotheses.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] The two forms of hypothesis testing are based on different problem formulations.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] The original test is analogous to a true/false question; the Neyman–Pearson test is more like multiple choice.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] In the view of Tukey the former produces a conclusion on the basis of only strong evidence while the latter produces a decision on the basis of available evidence.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] While the two tests seem quite different both mathematically and philosophically, later developments lead to the opposite claim.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] The hypotheses become 0,1,2,3... grains of radioactive sand.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] There is little distinction between none or some radiation (Fisher) and 0 grains of radioactive sand versus all of the alternatives (Neyman–Pearson).
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] The major Neyman–Pearson paper of 1933 also considered composite hypotheses (ones whose distribution includes an unknown parameter).
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] An example proved the optimality of the (Student's) *t*-test, "there can be no better test for the hypothesis under consideration" (p 321).
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Neyman–Pearson theory was proving the optimality of Fisherian methods from its inception.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Fisher's significance testing has proven a popular flexible statistical tool in application with little mathematical growth potential.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Neyman–Pearson hypothesis testing is claimed as a pillar of mathematical statistics, creating a new paradigm for the field.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] It also stimulated new applications in statistical process control, detection theory, decision theory and game theory.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Both formulations have been successful, but the successes have been of a different character.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] The dispute over formulations is unresolved.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Science primarily uses Fisher's (slightly modified) formulation as taught in introductory statistics.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Statisticians study Neyman–Pearson theory in graduate school.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Mathematicians are proud of uniting the formulations.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Learned opinions deem the formulations variously competitive (Fisher vs Neyman), incompatible or complementary.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] The dispute has become more complex since Bayesian inference has achieved respectability.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Hypothesis testing can mean any mixture of two formulations that both changed with time.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Any discussion of significance testing vs hypothesis testing is doubly vulnerable to confusion.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Fisher thought that hypothesis testing was a useful strategy for performing industrial quality control, however, he strongly disagreed that hypothesis testing could be useful for scientists.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Hypothesis testing provides a means of finding test statistics used in significance testing.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] The concept of power is useful in explaining the consequences of adjusting the significance level and is heavily used in sample size determination.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] The two methods remain philosophically distinct.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] They usually (but *not always*) produce the same mathematical answer.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] The preferred answer is context dependent.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] While the existing merger of Fisher and Neyman–Pearson theories has been heavily criticized, modifying the merger to achieve Bayesian goals has been considered.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Critics and supporters are largely in factual agreement regarding the characteristics of null hypothesis significance testing (NHST): While it can provide critical information, it is *inadequate as the sole tool for statistical analysis*.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] *Successfully rejecting the null hypothesis may offer no support for the research hypothesis.* The continuing controversy concerns the selection of the best statistical practices for the near-term future given the existing practices.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] However, adequate research design can minimize this issue.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Critics would prefer to ban NHST completely, forcing a complete departure from those practices, while supporters suggest a less absolute change.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Controversy over significance testing, and its effects on publication bias in particular, has produced several results.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Textbooks have added some cautions, and increased coverage of the tools necessary to estimate the size of the sample required to produce significant results.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Few major organizations have abandoned use of significance tests although some have discussed doing so.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] A unifying position of critics is that statistics should not lead to an accept-reject conclusion or decision, but to an estimated value with an interval estimate; this data-analysis philosophy is broadly referred to as estimation statistics.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Estimation statistics can be accomplished with either frequentist or Bayesian methods.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Critics of significance testing have advocated basing inference less on p-values and more on confidence intervals for effect sizes for importance, prediction intervals for confidence, replications and extensions for replicability, meta-analyses for generality :.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] But none of these suggested alternatives inherently produces a decision.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Bayesian inference is one proposed alternative to significance testing.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] (Nickerson cited 10 sources suggesting it, including Rozeboom (1960)).
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] For example, Bayesian parameter estimation can provide rich information about the data from which researchers can draw inferences, while using uncertain priors that exert only minimal influence on the results when enough data is available.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Kruschke has suggested Bayesian estimation as an alternative for the *t*-test and has also contrasted Bayesian estimation for assessing null values with Bayesian model comparison for hypothesis testing.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Two competing models/hypotheses can be compared using Bayes factors.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Bayesian methods could be criticized for requiring information that is seldom available in the cases where significance testing is most heavily used.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Neither the prior probabilities nor the probability distribution of the test statistic under the alternative hypothesis are often available in the social sciences.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Advocates of a Bayesian approach sometimes claim that the goal of a researcher is most often to objectively assess the probability that a hypothesis is true based on the data they have collected.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Neither Fisher's significance testing, nor Neyman–Pearson hypothesis testing can provide this information, and do not claim to.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] The probability a hypothesis is true can only be derived from use of Bayes' Theorem, which was unsatisfactory to both the Fisher and Neyman–Pearson camps due to the explicit use of subjectivity in the form of the prior probability.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-hypothesis-testing] Fisher's strategy is to sidestep this with the *p*-value (an objective *index* based on the data alone) followed by *inductive inference*, while Neyman–Pearson devised their approach of *inductive behaviour*.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] In frequentist statistics, **power** is the probability of detecting an effect (i.e. rejecting the null hypothesis) given that some prespecified effect actually exists using a given test in a given context.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] More formally, in the case of a simple hypothesis test with two hypotheses, the **power of the test** is the probability that the test correctly rejects the null hypothesis ( $H_{0}$ ) when the alternative hypothesis ( $H_{1}$ ) is true.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] It is commonly denoted by $1-\beta$ , where $\beta$ is the probability of making a type II error (a false negative) conditional on there being a true effect or association.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] Statistical testing uses data from samples to assess, or make inferences about, a statistical population.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] For example, we may measure the yields of samples of two varieties of a crop, and use a two sample test to assess whether the mean values of this yield differs between varieties.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] Under a frequentist hypothesis testing framework, this is done by calculating a test statistic (such as a t-statistic) for the dataset, which has a known theoretical probability distribution if there is no difference (the so-called null hypothesis).
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] If the actual value calculated on the sample is sufficiently unlikely to arise under the null hypothesis, we say we identified a statistically significant effect.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] The threshold for significance can be set small to ensure there is little chance of falsely detecting a non-existent effect.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] However, failing to identify a significant effect does not imply there was none.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] If we insist on being careful to avoid false positives, we may create false negatives instead.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] It may simply be too much to expect that we will be able to find satisfactorily strong evidence of a very subtle difference even if it exists.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] Statistical power is an attempt to quantify this issue.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] Suppose we are conducting a hypothesis test.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] We define two hypotheses $H_{0}$ the null hypothesis, and $H_{1}$ the alternative hypothesis.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] If we design the test such that *α* is the significance level (*α* being the probability of rejecting $H_{0}$ when $H_{0}$ is in fact true) then the power of the test is 1 − *β* where *β* is the probability of failing to reject $H_{0}$ when the alternative $H_{1}$ is true.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] To make this more concrete, a typical statistical test would be based on a test statistic *t* calculated from the sampled data, which has a particular probability distribution under $H_{0}$ .
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] A desired significance level *α* would then define a corresponding "rejection region" (bounded by certain "critical values"), a set of values *t* is unlikely to take if $H_{0}$ was correct.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] If we reject $H_{0}$ in favor of $H_{1}$ only when the sample *t* takes those values, we would be able to keep the probability of falsely rejecting $H_{0}$ within our desired significance level.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] Statistical power is one minus the type II error probability and is also the sensitivity of the hypothesis testing procedure to detect a true effect.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] There is usually a trade-off between demanding more stringent tests (and so, smaller rejection regions) and trying to have a high probability of rejecting the null under the alternative hypothesis.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] Statistical power may also be extended to the case where multiple hypotheses are being tested based on an experiment or survey.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] It is thus also common to refer to the **power of a study**, evaluating a scientific project in terms of its ability to answer the research questions they are seeking to answer.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] The main application of statistical power is "power analysis", a calculation of power usually done before an experiment is conducted using data from pilot studies or a literature review.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] Power analyses can be used to calculate the minimum sample size required so that one can be reasonably likely to detect an effect of a given size (in other words, producing an acceptable level of power).
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] For example: "How many times do I need to toss a coin to conclude it is rigged by a certain amount?" If resources and thus sample sizes are fixed, power analyses can also be used to calculate the minimum effect size that is likely to be detected.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] Funding agencies, ethics boards and research review panels frequently request that a researcher perform a power analysis.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] An underpowered study is likely be inconclusive, failing to allow one to choose between hypotheses at the desired significance level, while an overpowered study will spend great expense on being able to report significant effects even if they are tiny and so practically meaningless.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] If a large number of underpowered studies are done and statistically significant results published, published findings are more likely false positives than true results, contributing to a replication crisis.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] However, excessive demands for power could be connected to wasted resources and ethical problems, for example the use of a large number of animal test subjects when a smaller number would have been sufficient.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] It could also induce researchers trying to seek funding to overstate their expected effect sizes, or avoid looking for more subtle interaction effects that cannot be easily detected.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] Power analysis is primarily a frequentist statistics tool.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] In Bayesian statistics, hypothesis testing of the type used in classical power analysis is not done.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] In the Bayesian framework, one updates his or her prior beliefs using the data obtained in a given study.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] In principle, a study that would be deemed underpowered from the perspective of hypothesis testing could still be used in such an updating process.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] However, power remains a useful measure of how much a given experiment size can be expected to refine one's beliefs.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] A study with low power is unlikely to lead to a large change in beliefs.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] In addition, the concept of power is used to make comparisons between different statistical testing procedures: for example, between a parametric test and a nonparametric test of the same hypothesis.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] Tests may have the same size, and hence the same false positive rates, but different ability to detect true effects.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] Consideration of their theoretical power proprieties is a key reason for the common use of likelihood ratio tests.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] This expression can be rearranged, implying for example that 80% power is obtained when looking for a difference in means that exceeds about 4 times the group-wise standard error of the mean.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] For a one sample t-test 16 is to be replaced with 8.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] Other values provide an appropriate approximation when the desired power or significance level are different.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] However, a full power analysis should always be performed to confirm and refine this estimate.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] Statistical power may depend on a number of factors.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] For a given test, the **significance criterion** determines the desired degree of rigor, specifying how unlikely it is for the null hypothesis of no effect to be rejected if it is in fact true.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] The most commonly used threshold is a probability of rejection of 0.05, though smaller values like 0.01 or 0.001 are sometimes used.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] This threshold then implies that the observation must be at least that unlikely (perhaps by suggesting a sufficiently large estimate of difference) to be considered strong enough evidence against the null.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] Picking a smaller value to tighten the threshold, so as to reduce the chance of a false positive, would also reduce power (and so increase the chance of a false negative).
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] Some statistical tests will inherently produce better power, albeit often at the cost of requiring stronger assumptions.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] The **magnitude of the effect** of interest defines what is being looked for by the test.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] It can be the expected effect size if it exists, as a scientific hypothesis that the researcher has arrived at and wishes to test.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] Alternatively, in a more practical context it could be determined by the size the effect must be to be useful, for example that which is required to be clinically significant.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] An effect size can be a direct value of the quantity of interest (for example, a difference in mean of a particular size), or it can be a standardized measure that also accounts for the variability in the population (such as a difference in means expressed as a multiple of the standard deviation).
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] If the researcher is looking for a larger effect, then it should be easier to find with a given experimental or analytic setup, and so power is higher.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] The nature of the **sample** underlies the information being used in the test.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] This will usually involve the sample size, and the sample variability, if that is not implicit in the definition of the effect size.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] More broadly, the precision with which the data are measured can also be an important factor (such as the statistical reliability), as well as the design of an experiment or observational study.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] Ultimately, these factors lead to an expected amount of sampling error.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] How increased sample size translates to higher power is a measure of the efficiency of the test—for example, the sample size required for a given power.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] The statistical power of a hypothesis test has an impact on the interpretation of its results.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] Not finding a result with a more powerful study is stronger evidence against the effect existing than the same finding with a less powerful study.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] However, this is not completely conclusive.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] The effect may exist, but be smaller than what was looked for, meaning the study is in fact underpowered and the sample is thus unable to distinguish it from random chance.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] Many clinical trials, for instance, have low statistical power to detect differences in adverse effects of treatments, since such effects may only affect a few patients, even if this difference can be important.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] Conclusions about the probability of actual presence of an effect also should consider more things than a single test, especially as real world power is rarely close to 1.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] Indeed, although there are no formal standards for power, many researchers and funding bodies assess power using 0.80 (or 80%) as a standard for adequacy.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] This convention implies a four-to-one trade off between β-risk and α-risk, as the probability of a type II error β is set as 1 - 0.8 = 0.2, while α, the probability of a type I error, is commonly set at 0.05.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] Some applications require much higher levels of power.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] Medical tests may be designed to minimise the number of false negatives (type II errors) produced by loosening the threshold of significance, raising the risk of obtaining a false positive (a type I error).
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] Power analysis focuses on the correct rejection of a null hypothesis.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] Alternative concerns may however motivate an experiment, and so lead to different needs for sample size.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] In many contexts, the issue is less about deciding between hypotheses but rather with getting an estimate of the population effect size of sufficient accuracy.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] For example, a careful power analysis can tell you that 55 pairs of normally distributed samples with a correlation of 0.5 will be sufficient to grant 80% power in rejecting a null that the correlation is no more than 0.2 (using a one-sided test, α = 0.05).
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] But the typical 95% confidence interval with this sample would be around [0.27, 0.67].
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] An alternative, albeit related analysis would be required if we wish to be able to measure correlation to an accuracy of ± 0.1, implying a different (in this case, larger) sample size.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] Alternatively, multiple under-powered studies can still be useful, if appropriately combined through a meta-analysis.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] Many statistical analyses involve the estimation of several unknown quantities.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] In simple cases, all but one of these quantities are nuisance parameters.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] In this setting, the only relevant power pertains to the single quantity that will undergo formal statistical inference.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] In some settings, particularly if the goals are more "exploratory", there may be a number of quantities of interest in the analysis.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] For example, in a multiple regression analysis we may include several covariates of potential interest.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] In situations such as this where several hypotheses are under consideration, it is common that the powers associated with the different hypotheses differ.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] For instance, in multiple regression analysis, the power for detecting an effect of a given size is related to the variance of the covariate.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] Since different covariates will have different variances, their powers will differ as well.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] Additional complications arise when we consider these multiple hypotheses together.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] For example, if we consider a false positive to be making an erroneous null rejection on any one of these hypotheses, our likelihood of this "family-wise error" will be inflated if appropriate measures are not taken.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] Such measures typically involve applying a higher threshold of stringency to reject a hypothesis (such as with the Bonferroni method), and so would reduce power.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] Alternatively, there may be different notions of power connected with how the different hypotheses are considered.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] "Complete power" demands that all true effects are detected across all of the hypotheses, which is a much stronger requirement than the "minimal power" of being able to find at least one true effect, a type of power that might increase with an increasing number of hypotheses.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] Power analysis can either be done before (*a priori* or prospective power analysis) or after (*post hoc* or retrospective power analysis) data are collected.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] *A priori* power analysis is conducted prior to the research study, and is typically used in estimating sufficient sample sizes to achieve adequate power.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] *Post-hoc* analysis of "observed power" is conducted after a study has been completed, and uses the obtained sample size and effect size to determine what the power was in the study, assuming the effect size in the sample is equal to the effect size in the population.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] Whereas the utility of prospective power analysis in experimental design is universally accepted, post hoc power analysis is controversial.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] Many statisticians have argued that post-hoc power calculations are misleading and essentially meaningless.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] We are interested in being able to detect a positive change of size $\theta >0$ .
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] We first set up the problem according to our test.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] Let $A_{i}$ and $B_{i}$ denote the pre-treatment and post-treatment measures on subject i , respectively.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] The possible effect of the treatment should be visible in the differences $D_{i}=B_{i}-A_{i},$ which are assumed to be independent and identically Normal in distribution, with unknown mean value $\mu _{D}$ and variance $\sigma _{D}^{2}$ .
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] and ${\hat {\sigma }}_{D}$ is the sample standard deviation of the difference.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] We can proceed according to our knowledge of statistical theory, though in practice for a standard case like this software will exist to compute more accurate answers.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] Thanks to t-test theory, we know this test statistic under the null hypothesis follows a Student t-distribution with $n-1$ degrees of freedom.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] If we wish to reject the null at significance level $\alpha =0.05\,$ , we must find the critical value $t_{\alpha }$ such that the probability of $T_{n}>t_{\alpha }$ under the null is equal to $\alpha$ .
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] Now suppose that the alternative hypothesis $H_{1}$ is true so $\mu _{D}=\theta$ .
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] Then, writing the power as a function of the effect size, $B(\theta )$ , we find the probability of $T_{n}$ being above $t_{\alpha }$ under $H_{1}$ .
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] ${\frac {{\bar {D}}_{n}-\theta }{{\hat {\sigma }}_{D}/{\sqrt {n}}}}$ again follows a student-t distribution under $H_{1}$ , converging on to a standard normal distribution for large n.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] According to this formula, the power increases with the values of the effect size $\theta$ and the sample size n, and reduces with increasing variability $\sigma _{D}$ .
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] In the trivial case of zero effect size, power is at a minimum (infimum) and equal to the significance level of the test $\alpha \,,$ in this example 0.05.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] For finite sample sizes and non-zero variability, it is the case here, as is typical, that power cannot be made equal to 1 except in the trivial case where $\alpha =1$ so the null is *always* rejected.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] Alternatively we can use a Monte Carlo simulation method that works more generally.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] Once again, we return to the assumption of the distribution of $D_{n}$ and the definition of $T_{n}$ .
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] Suppose we have fixed values of the sample size, variability and effect size, and wish to compute power.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] Compute the resulting test statistic $T_{n}$ for each set.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] Compute the $(1-\alpha )$ th quantile of the simulated $T_{n}$ and use that as an estimate of $t_{\alpha }$ .
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] Now generate a large number of sets of $D_{n}$ according to the alternative hypothesis, $N(\theta ,\sigma _{D})$ , and compute the corresponding test statistics again.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] Look at the proportion of these simulated alternative $T_{n}$ that are above the $t_{\alpha }$ calculated in step 3 and so are rejected.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] This can be done with a variety of software packages.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] Using this methodology with the values before, setting the sample size to 25 leads to an estimated power of around 0.78.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] The small discrepancy with the previous section is due mainly to inaccuracies with the normal approximation.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] Several studies have attempted to estimate typical levels of statistical power across different academic fields.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] One common approach uses meta-analyses to assess whether individual studies have sufficient power to detect the average effect size estimated from the meta-analysis itself.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] This method essentially asks: how likely is each study to detect the consensus effect found in the broader literature?
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] These assessments consistently find low levels of statistical power across many disciplines.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] For example, using this method median power is 18% in economics, 10% in political science, 36% in psychology, and 15% in ecology and evolutionary biology.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] In the frequentist setting, parameters are assumed to have a specific value which is unlikely to be true.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] This issue can be addressed by assuming the parameter has a distribution.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] The resulting power is sometimes referred to as Bayesian power which is commonly used in clinical trial design.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] Both frequentist power and Bayesian power use statistical significance as the success criterion.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] However, statistical significance is often not enough to define success.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] To address this issue, the power concept can be extended to the concept of predictive probability of success (PPOS).
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] The success criterion for PPOS is not restricted to statistical significance and is commonly used in clinical trial designs.
[src:biostatistics/statistical-power] Numerous free and/or open source programs are available for performing power and sample size calculations.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] To answer such questions, it is necessary to define "lifetime".
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] In the case of biological survival, death is unambiguous, but for mechanical reliability, failure may not be well-defined, for there may well be mechanical systems in which failure is partial, a matter of degree, or not otherwise localized in time.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] Even in biological problems, some events (for example, heart attack or other organ failure) may have the same ambiguity.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] The theory outlined below assumes well-defined events at specific times; other cases may be better treated by models which explicitly account for ambiguous events.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] More generally, survival analysis involves the modelling of time to event data; in this context, death or failure is considered an "event" in the survival analysis literature – traditionally only a single event occurs for each subject, after which the organism or mechanism is dead or broken.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] *Recurring event* or *repeated event* models relax that assumption.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] The study of recurring events is relevant in systems reliability, and in many areas of social sciences and medical research.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] This example uses the Acute Myelogenous Leukemia survival data set "aml" from the "survival" package in R.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] The data set is from Miller (1997) and the question is whether the standard course of chemotherapy should be extended ('maintained') for additional cycles.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] The aml data set sorted by survival time is shown in the box.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] The last observation (11), at 161 weeks, is censored.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] Censoring indicates that the patient did not have an event (no recurrence of aml cancer).
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] Another subject, observation 3, was censored at 13 weeks (indicated by status=0).
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] This subject was in the study for only 13 weeks, and the aml cancer did not recur during those 13 weeks.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] It is possible that this patient was enrolled near the end of the study, so that they could be observed for only 13 weeks.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] It is also possible that the patient was enrolled early in the study, but was lost to follow up or withdrew from the study.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] The table shows that other subjects were censored at 16, 28, and 45 weeks (observations 17, 6, and 9 with status=0).
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] The remaining subjects all experienced events (recurrence of aml cancer) while in the study.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] The question of interest is whether recurrence occurs later in maintained patients than in non-maintained patients.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] The survival function *S*(*t*), is the probability that a subject survives longer than time *t*.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] *S*(*t*) is theoretically a smooth curve, but it is usually estimated using the Kaplan–Meier (KM) curve.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] A life table summarizes survival data in terms of the number of events and the proportion surviving at each event time point.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] The life table for the aml data, created using the R software, is shown.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] The life table summarizes the events and the proportion surviving at each event time point.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] The log-rank test compares the survival times of two or more groups.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] This example uses a log-rank test for a difference in survival in the maintained versus non-maintained treatment groups in the aml data.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] The graph shows KM plots for the aml data broken out by treatment group, which is indicated by the variable "x" in the data.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] The null hypothesis for a log-rank test is that the groups have the same survival.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] The expected number of subjects surviving at each time point in each is adjusted for the number of subjects at risk in the groups at each event time.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] The log-rank test determines if the observed number of events in each group is significantly different from the expected number.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] The formal test is based on a chi-squared statistic.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] When the log-rank statistic is large, it is evidence for a difference in the survival times between the groups.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] The log-rank statistic approximately has a Chi-squared distribution with one degree of freedom, and the p-value is calculated using the Chi-squared test.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] For the example data, the log-rank test for difference in survival gives a p-value of p=0.0653, indicating that the treatment groups do not differ significantly in survival, assuming an alpha level of 0.05.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] The sample size of 23 subjects is modest, so there is little power to detect differences between the treatment groups.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] The chi-squared test is based on asymptotic approximation, so the p-value should be regarded with caution for small sample sizes.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] Kaplan–Meier curves and log-rank tests are most useful when the predictor variable is categorical (e.g., drug vs. placebo), or takes a small number of values (e.g., drug doses 0, 20, 50, and 100 mg/day) that can be treated as categorical.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] The log-rank test and KM curves don't work easily with quantitative predictors such as gene expression, white blood count, or age.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] For quantitative predictor variables, an alternative method is Cox proportional hazards regression analysis.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] Cox PH models work also with categorical predictor variables, which are encoded as {0,1} indicator or dummy variables.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] The log-rank test is a special case of a Cox PH analysis, and can be performed using Cox PH software.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] This example uses the melanoma data set from Dalgaard Chapter 14.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] The Cox proportional hazards regression using R gives the results shown in the box.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] The Cox regression results are interpreted as follows.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] The summary output also gives upper and lower 95% confidence intervals for the hazard ratio: lower 95% bound = 1.15; upper 95% bound = 3.26.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] These three tests are asymptotically equivalent.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] For large enough N, they will give similar results.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] The last row, "Score (logrank) test" is the result for the log-rank test, with p=0.011, the same result as the log-rank test, because the log-rank test is a special case of a Cox PH regression.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] The Likelihood ratio test has better behavior for small sample sizes, so it is generally preferred.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] The Cox model extends the log-rank test by allowing the inclusion of additional covariates.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] This example uses the melanoma data set where the predictor variables include a continuous covariate, the thickness of the tumor (variable name = "thick").
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] In the histograms, the thickness values are positively skewed and do not have a Gaussian-like, symmetric probability distribution.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] Regression models, including the Cox model, generally give more reliable results with normally-distributed variables.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] For this example we may use a logarithmic transform.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] The log of the thickness of the tumor looks to be more normally distributed, so the Cox models will use log thickness.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] The Cox PH analysis using R gives the results below.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] The p-value for all three overall tests (likelihood, Wald, and score) are significant, indicating that the model is significant.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] The p-value for $\log({\text{thick}})$ is 6.94×10−7, with a hazard ratio $HR=\exp({\text{coef}})=2.183$ , indicating a strong relationship between the thickness of the tumor and increased risk of death.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] Because the confidence interval for HR includes 1, these results indicate that sex makes a smaller contribution to the difference in the HR after controlling for the thickness of the tumor.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] Examination of graphs of $log({\text{thick}})$ by sex and a t-test of $log({\text{thick}})$ by sex both indicate that there is a significant difference between men and women in the thickness of the tumor when they first see the clinician.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] The Cox model assumes that the hazards are proportional.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] The proportional hazard assumption may be tested using the R function `cox.zph()` from the survival R package.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] A p-value which is less than 0.05 indicates that the hazards are not proportional.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] For the melanoma data, we obtain $p=0.248$ for sex.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] Hence, we cannot reject the null hypothesis of the hazards of sex being proportional.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] Cox models can be extended to deal with variations on the simple analysis.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] The Cox PH regression model is a linear model.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] It is similar to linear regression and logistic regression.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] Specifically, these methods assume that a single line, curve, plane, or surface is sufficient to separate groups (alive, dead) or to estimate a quantitative response (survival time).
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] In some cases alternative partitions give more accurate classification or quantitative estimates.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] One set of alternative methods are tree-structured survival models, including survival random forests.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] Tree-structured survival models may give more accurate predictions than Cox models.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] Examining both types of models for a given data set is a reasonable strategy.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] This example of a survival tree analysis uses the R package "rpart".
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] The example is based on 146 stage C prostate cancer patients in the data set stagec in rpart.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] Rpart and the stagec example are described in Atkinson and Therneau (1997), which is also distributed as a vignette of the rpart package.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] The survival tree produced by the analysis is shown in the figure.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] Each branch in the tree indicates a split on the value of a variable.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] For example, the root of the tree splits subjects with grade < 2.5 versus subjects with grade 2.5 or greater.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] The terminal nodes indicate the number of subjects in the node, the number of subjects who have events, and the relative event rate compared to the root.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] In the node on the far left, the values 1/33 indicate that one of the 33 subjects in the node had an event, and that the relative event rate is 0.122.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] In the node on the far right bottom, the values 11/15 indicate that 11 of 15 subjects in the node had an event, and the relative event rate is 2.7.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] An alternative to building a single survival tree is to build many survival trees, where each tree is constructed using a sample of the data, and average the trees to predict survival.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] This is the method underlying the survival random forest models.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] Survival random forest analysis is available in the R package "randomForestSRC".
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] The randomForestSRC package includes an example survival random forest analysis using the data set pbc.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] This data is from the Mayo Clinic Primary Biliary Cirrhosis (PBC) trial of the liver conducted between 1974 and 1984.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] In the example, the random forest survival model gives more accurate predictions of survival than the Cox PH model.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] The prediction errors are estimated by bootstrap re-sampling.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] Recent advancements in deep representation learning have been extended to survival estimation.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] The DeepSurv model proposes to replace the log-linear parameterization of the CoxPH model with a multi-layer perceptron.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] Further extensions like Deep Survival Machines and Deep Cox Mixtures involve the use of latent variable mixture models to model the time-to-event distribution as a mixture of parametric or semi-parametric distributions while jointly learning representations of the input covariates.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] Deep learning approaches have shown superior performance especially on complex input data modalities such as images and clinical time-series.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] The object of primary interest is the **survival function**, conventionally denoted *S*, which is defined as $S(t)=\Pr(T>t)$ where *t* is some time, *T* is a random variable denoting the time of death, or more generally any event, and "Pr" stands for probability.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] That is, the survival function is the probability of observing an event time greater than some specified time *t*.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] The survival function is also called the *survivor function* or *survivorship function* in problems of biological survival, and the *reliability function* in mechanical survival problems.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] In the latter case, the reliability function is denoted *R*(*t*).
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] Usually one assumes *S*(0) = 1, although it could be less than 1 if there is the possibility of immediate death or failure.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] The survival function must be non-increasing: *S*(*u*) ≤ *S*(*t*) if *u* ≥ *t*.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] This property follows directly because *T*>*u* implies *T*>*t*.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] This reflects the notion that survival to a later age is possible only if all younger ages are attained.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] Given this property, the lifetime distribution function and event density (*F* and *f* below) are well-defined.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] The survival function is usually assumed to approach zero as age increases without bound (i.e., *S*(*t*) → 0 as *t* → ∞), although the limit could be greater than zero if eternal life is possible.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] For instance, we could apply survival analysis to a mixture of stable and unstable carbon isotopes; unstable isotopes would decay sooner or later, but the stable isotopes would last indefinitely.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] Related quantities are defined in terms of the survival function.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] $f(t)=F'(t)={\frac {d}{dt}}F(t).$ The function *f* is sometimes called the **event density**; it is the rate of death or failure events per unit time.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] $s(t)=S'(t)={\frac {d}{dt}}S(t)={\frac {d}{dt}}\int _{t}^{\infty }f(u)\,du={\frac {d}{dt}}[1-F(t)]=-f(t).$ In other fields, such as statistical physics, the survival event density function is known as the first passage time density.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] Synonyms for *hazard function* in different fields include hazard rate, intensity function, force of mortality (demography and actuarial science, denoted by $\mu$ ), force of failure, or failure rate (engineering, denoted $\lambda$ ).
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] For example, in actuarial science, $\mu (x)$ denotes rate of death for people aged x , whereas in reliability engineering $\lambda (t)$ denotes rate of failure of components after operation for time t .
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] The hazard function represents the probability that a subject will experience an event in the next small interval of time, divided by the length of this interval, given that they have survived up to time t .
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] where Bayes' theorem, and identifying $\Pr(T>t)$ as the survival function, has been used in the first equality, and the definition of the density function of the lifetime distribution in the second.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] In fact, the hazard rate is usually more informative about the underlying mechanism of failure than the other representations of a lifetime distribution.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] The hazard function must be non-negative, $\lambda (t)\geq 0$ , and its integral over $[0,\infty ]$ must be infinite, but is not otherwise constrained; it may be increasing or decreasing, non-monotonic, or discontinuous.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] An example is the bathtub curve hazard function, which is large for small values of t , decreasing to some minimum, and thereafter increasing again; this can model the property of some mechanical systems to either fail soon after operation, or much later, as the system ages.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] $\Lambda (t)=\int _{0}^{t}\lambda (u)\,du$ which is the "accumulation" of the hazard over time.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] From the definition of $\Lambda (t)$ , we see that it increases without bound as *t* tends to infinity (assuming that $S(t)$ tends to zero).
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] This implies that $\lambda (t)$ must not decrease too quickly, since, by definition, the cumulative hazard has to diverge.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] For example, $\exp(-t)$ is not the hazard function of any survival distribution, because its integral converges to 1.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] For $t_{0}=0$ , that is, at birth, this reduces to the expected lifetime.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] In reliability problems, the expected lifetime is called the *mean time to failure*, and the expected future lifetime is called the *mean residual lifetime*.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] As the probability of an individual surviving until age *t* or later is *S*(*t*), by definition, the expected number of survivors at age *t* out of an initial population of *n* newborns is *n* × *S*(*t*), assuming the same survival function for all individuals.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] Thus the expected proportion of survivors is *S*(*t*).
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] If the survival of different individuals is independent, the number of survivors at age *t* has a binomial distribution with parameters *n* and *S*(*t*), and the variance of the proportion of survivors is *S*(*t*) × (1-*S*(*t*))/*n*.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] The age at which a specified proportion of survivors remain can be found by solving the equation *S*(*t*) = *q* for *t*, where *q* is the quantile in question.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] Typically one is interested in the **median lifetime**, for which *q* = 1/2, or other quantiles such as *q* = 0.90 or *q* = 0.99.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] Censoring is a form of missing data problem in which time to event is not observed for reasons such as termination of study before all recruited subjects have shown the event of interest or the subject has left the study prior to experiencing an event.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] Censoring is common in survival analysis.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] If only the lower limit *l* for the true event time *T* is known such that *T* > *l*, this is called *right censoring*.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] Right censoring will occur, for example, for those subjects whose birth date is known but who are still alive when they are lost to follow-up or when the study ends.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] We generally encounter right-censored data.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] If the event of interest has already happened before the subject is included in the study but it is not known when it occurred, the data is said to be *left-censored*.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] When it can only be said that the event happened between two observations or examinations, this is *interval censoring*.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] Left censoring occurs for example when a permanent tooth has already emerged prior to the start of a dental study that aims to estimate its emergence distribution.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] In the same study, an emergence time is interval-censored when the permanent tooth is present in the mouth at the current examination but not yet at the previous examination.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] Interval censoring often occurs in HIV/AIDS studies.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] Indeed, time to HIV seroconversion can be determined only by a laboratory assessment which is usually initiated after a visit to the physician.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] Then one can only conclude that HIV seroconversion has happened between two examinations.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] The same is true for the diagnosis of AIDS, which is based on clinical symptoms and needs to be confirmed by a medical examination.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] It may also happen that subjects with a lifetime less than some threshold may not be observed at all: this is called *truncation*.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] Note that truncation is different from left censoring, since for a left censored datum, we know the subject exists, but for a truncated datum, we may be completely unaware of the subject.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] In a so-called *delayed entry* study, subjects are not observed at all until they have reached a certain age.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] For example, people may not be observed until they have reached the age to enter school.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] Any deceased subjects in the pre-school age group would be unknown.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] Left-truncated data are common in actuarial work for life insurance and pensions.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] Left-censored data can occur when a person's survival time becomes incomplete on the left side of the follow-up period for the person.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] For example, in an epidemiological example, we may monitor a patient for an infectious disorder starting from the time when he or she is tested positive for the infection.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] Although we may know the right-hand side of the duration of interest, we may never know the exact time of exposure to the infectious agent.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] Survival models can be usefully viewed as ordinary regression models in which the response variable is time.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] However, computing the likelihood function (needed for fitting parameters or making other kinds of inferences) is complicated by the censoring.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] The likelihood function for a survival model, in the presence of censored data, is formulated as follows.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] By definition the likelihood function is the conditional probability of the data given the parameters of the model.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] It is customary to assume that the data are independent given the parameters.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] Then the likelihood function is the product of the likelihood of each datum.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] It is convenient to partition the data into four categories: uncensored, left censored, right censored, and interval censored.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] These are denoted "unc.", "l.c.", "r.c.", and "i.c." in the equation below.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] The Kaplan–Meier estimator can be used to estimate the survival function.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] The Nelson–Aalen estimator can be used to provide a non-parametric estimate of the cumulative hazard rate function.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] Periodic case (cohort) and death (and recovery) counts are statistically sufficient to make nonparametric maximum likelihood and least squares estimates of survival functions, without lifetime data.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] While many parametric models assume a continuous-time, discrete-time survival models can be mapped to a binary classification problem.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] In a discrete-time survival model the survival period is artificially resampled in intervals where for each interval a binary target indicator is recorded if the event takes place in a certain time horizon.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] If a binary classifier (potentially enhanced with a different likelihood to take more structure of the problem into account) is calibrated, then the classifier score is the hazard function (i.e. the conditional probability of failure).
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] Discrete-time survival models are connected to empirical likelihood.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] Instead of performing the time-discretization and bringing the data in this long-format, an alternative way is to perform distributional regression over the binned time-axis.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] This approach can leverage prior data fitted networks (tabular foundation models) to work with small data sets already.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] The goodness of fit of survival models can be assessed using scoring rules.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] A cure model allows for the possibility that some individuals never experience the event of interest.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] This creates survival curves that plateau rather than always converging to zero.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] First term: cured individuals, who survive indefinitely.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] Second term: susceptible individuals, whose survival declines according to the hazard.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] Without a cure model, survival is forced to zero in the limit of large times.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] The textbook by Kleinbaum has examples of survival analyses using SAS, R, and other packages.
[src:biostatistics/survival-analysis] The textbooks by Brostrom, Dalgaard and Tableman and Kim give examples of survival analyses using R (or using S, and which run in R).
